Your mutex isn't shared вҖ” it's the concurrency equivalent of everyone bringing their own key to a lock and wondering why the door doesn't stay closed.

**"Per-operation mutex"** means each concurrent call creates (or acquires) its own mutex instance. Two operations racing on the same record each lock *their own* mutex, both read the same stale value, both pass the condition check, both write. The mutex is functioning perfectly; it's just not contending with anything.

## The fix

The mutex must be **per-resource**, not per-operation. Every operation touching the same logical record must contend on the same lock:

```
// BROKEN: each call gets its own lock
async function transferFunds(accountId, amount) {
  const mu = new Mutex();        // вҶҗ new instance every time
  await mu.acquire();
  const balance = await db.read(accountId);
  if (balance >= amount) {
    await db.write(accountId, balance - amount);
  }
  mu.release();
}

// FIXED: lock is keyed to the resource
const locks = new Map();  // accountId вҶ’ Mutex

function getLock(accountId) {
  if (!locks.has(accountId)) locks.set(accountId, new Mutex());
  return locks.get(accountId);
}

async function transferFunds(accountId, amount) {
  const mu = getLock(accountId);  // вҶҗ same account = same lock
  await mu.acquire();
  try {
    const balance = await db.read(accountId);
    if (balance >= amount) {
      await db.write(accountId, balance - amount);
    }
  } finally {
    mu.release();
  }
}
```

## But consider whether an application-level mutex is the right tool at all

The deeper trade-off: **application-level locks don't survive across multiple server instances.** If you're running more than one replica (or ever will), the per-resource mutex works on a single node but breaks again when the same account is hit on two different servers.

The more durable fix is pushing the atomicity down to the database:

- **Optimistic concurrency**: add a version column, `UPDATE accounts SET balance = $new, version = version + 1 WHERE id = $id AND version = $expected`. If zero rows affected, retry. No application lock needed.
- **Database-level locking**: `SELECT ... FOR UPDATE` makes the database hold the row lock across your read-check-write within a transaction.

Optimistic concurrency is usually the better default вҖ” it scales horizontally without coordination, and under low contention (which is the common case), it almost never retries. `SELECT FOR UPDATE` is simpler to reason about but holds a row lock for the duration of your application logic, which can become a bottleneck.

For your immediate fix: make the mutex per-resource. For your next iteration: move the atomicity guarantee into the database so it works regardless of how many application instances you run.

Since this project is Dart, I'll write it in Dart. The key trade-off is regex complexity vs. correctness вҖ” RFC 5322 is notoriously byzantine, so I'll target the practical subset that covers real-world emails rather than chasing full spec compliance.

```dart
/// Validates an email address against practical real-world rules.
///
/// Checks structure (local@domain), character validity, and domain format.
/// Does NOT attempt full RFC 5322 compliance вҖ” intentionally rejects quoted
/// strings and comments that are technically valid but never seen in practice.
bool isValidEmail(String email) {
  if (email.length > 254) return false; // SMTP limit

  final parts = email.split('@');
  if (parts.length != 2) return false;

  final local = parts[0];
  final domain = parts[1];

  // Local part: 1-64 chars, alphanumeric + . _ % + -
  // No leading/trailing/consecutive dots
  if (local.isEmpty ||
      local.length > 64 ||
      local.startsWith('.') ||
      local.endsWith('.') ||
      local.contains('..')) {
    return false;
  }
  if (!RegExp(r'^[a-zA-Z0-9._%+-]+$').hasMatch(local)) return false;

  // Domain: at least one dot, each label 1-63 chars, alphanumeric + hyphens
  // No leading/trailing hyphens per label, TLD must be alphabetic
  final labels = domain.split('.');
  if (labels.length < 2) return false;

  for (final label in labels) {
    if (label.isEmpty ||
        label.length > 63 ||
        label.startsWith('-') ||
        label.endsWith('-')) {
      return false;
    }
    if (!RegExp(r'^[a-zA-Z0-9-]+$').hasMatch(label)) return false;
  }

  // TLD must be at least 2 chars and purely alphabetic
  final tld = labels.last;
  if (tld.length < 2 || !RegExp(r'^[a-zA-Z]+$').hasMatch(tld)) return false;

  return true;
}
```

The function validates in layers вҖ” length limits first (cheap), then structural split on `@`, then local-part rules, then domain label-by-label. Each check corresponds to a real failure mode:

- **254-char total limit**: SMTP path length, not just convention
- **Consecutive dots in local part**: Every major provider rejects these, and they're a common typo signal
- **Alphabetic TLD**: Rejects `user@domain.123` which catches IP-address-style domains that slipped past the `@` split (if you need IP literals like `[192.168.1.1]`, that's a different function with different trust assumptions)

What it intentionally *won't* catch: whether the domain has MX records. That's a network call, not a validation function вҖ” mix those concerns and you get timeouts in form handlers.

This question is genuinely exciting because almost everyone gets it wrong in the same way. They model **notation** вҖ” pitch 60, duration 0.5, velocity 80 вҖ” which is to music what pixel coordinates are to painting. You've captured the *where* and lost the *what*.

Here's the core insight that should drive the design: **music is relational, not absolute.** A melody transposed up a fifth is the same melody. A rhythm at 120bpm and 60bpm is the same rhythm. The identity of musical ideas lives in the *relationships between* things, not in the things themselves.

Let me sketch this in Dart since that's what's on the workbench:

```dart
// в”Җв”Җв”Җ THE ACTUAL PRIMITIVES в”Җв”Җв”Җ
// Not pitches. Not durations. Relationships.

/// An interval is the atom of melody and harmony.
/// Not "C4" but "a minor third up from wherever you are."
sealed class Interval {
  const Interval(this.semitones);
  final int semitones;

  Interval operator +(Interval other) => Interval(semitones + other.semitones);
  Interval operator -() => Interval(-semitones);

  // Named constructors read like music theory
  const factory Interval.unison() = _Fixed.new(0);
  const factory Interval.minorSecond() = _Fixed.new(1);
  const factory Interval.majorThird() = _Fixed.new(4);
  const factory Interval.perfectFifth() = _Fixed.new(7);
  // ... you get it
}

/// Scale degree вҖ” position within a tonal context.
/// This is how musicians actually think. "The third" not "E".
class ScaleDegree {
  final int degree;       // 1-7
  final Alteration alt;   // natural, sharp, flat

  // "The flatted seventh" is a musical concept. 
  // "Bb" is an implementation detail.
  const ScaleDegree(this.degree, [this.alt = Alteration.natural]);
}

/// Rhythm as proportion, not duration.
/// A dotted quarter followed by an eighth is 3:1, 
/// regardless of tempo.
sealed class RhythmicPattern {
  const RhythmicPattern();
}

class Pulse extends RhythmicPattern {
  /// Weight relative to surrounding pulses.
  /// This is how you encode swing, groove, syncopation вҖ”
  /// not as "delay" but as *emphasis*.
  final double weight;
  const Pulse({this.weight = 1.0});
}

class Division extends RhythmicPattern {
  /// Proportional subdivisions. [3, 1] = dotted-quarter + eighth.
  /// [2, 2, 2] = triplet. [1] = a single undivided beat.
  final List<int> proportions;
  final List<RhythmicPattern> children;
  const Division(this.proportions, this.children);
}
```

Now here's where it gets interesting вҖ” **the composition layer**. Music has exactly two fundamental operations: *sequential* (this then that) and *simultaneous* (this with that). Everything else вҖ” form, orchestration, counterpoint вҖ” is built from composing these two:

```dart
/// The core algebraic structure. Music is a monoid
/// under sequential composition, with simultaneous 
/// composition as a second operation.
sealed class Music<A> {
  const Music();

  /// The two fundamental operations
  Music<A> then(Music<A> other) => Sequential([this, other]);
  Music<A> with_(Music<A> other) => Simultaneous([this, other]);

  /// And the transformations that preserve musical identity
  Music<A> transpose(Interval i);
  Music<A> invert();          // flip intervals
  Music<A> retrograde();      // reverse time
  Music<A> augment(int n);    // stretch rhythm proportionally
  Music<A> diminish(int n);   // compress rhythm proportionally
}

/// A single sounding event вҖ” but note what's NOT here.
/// No absolute pitch. No absolute duration.
class Note extends Music<Interval> {
  final Interval interval;      // from what? context determines this
  final RhythmicPattern rhythm;
  final Intensity intensity;
  const Note(this.interval, this.rhythm, this.intensity);
}

class Rest extends Music<Never> {
  final RhythmicPattern rhythm;
  const Rest(this.rhythm);
}

class Sequential<A> extends Music<A> {
  final List<Music<A>> elements;
  const Sequential(this.elements);
}

class Simultaneous<A> extends Music<A> {
  final List<Music<A>> voices;
  const Simultaneous(this.voices);
}
```

Now вҖ” **harmonic function**. This is the part nobody models well. A V chord isn't just "the notes G-B-D." It's a *tension that wants to resolve to I*. That desire is the musical concept:

```dart
/// Harmony as function, not as pitch collection.
class HarmonicFunction {
  final ScaleDegree root;
  final ChordQuality quality;
  final Tendency tendency;  // вҶҗ THIS is the interesting part

  const HarmonicFunction(this.root, this.quality, this.tendency);
}

/// Where does this harmony "want" to go?
/// This encodes centuries of voice-leading intuition.
sealed class Tendency {
  const Tendency();
}

class Resolves extends Tendency {
  final ScaleDegree target;
  final double urgency;  // VвҶ’I is urgent. IVвҶ’I is gentle.
  const Resolves(this.target, {this.urgency = 0.5});
}

class Prolongs extends Tendency {
  final ScaleDegree prolonged;  // I-vi-IV-I prolongs tonic
  const Prolongs(this.prolonged);
}

class Destabilizes extends Tendency {
  const Destabilizes();  // diminished chords, augmented 6ths вҖ” pure tension
}
```

And **dynamics as narrative arc**, not velocity values:

```dart
/// Dynamics are relative and directional.
/// "Getting louder" is a musical concept.
/// "Velocity 96" is a MIDI artifact.
sealed class Intensity {
  const Intensity();
}

class Stable extends Intensity {
  final double level;  // 0.0 to 1.0, relative to context
  const Stable(this.level);
}

class Changing extends Intensity {
  final double from;
  final double to;
  final IntensityCurve curve;  // linear, exponential, sudden
  const Changing(this.from, this.to, this.curve);
}

/// The real power: intensity as expression marking
class Expressive extends Intensity {
  final Expression expression;
  const Expressive(this.expression);
}

enum Expression {
  dolce,        // sweetly вҖ” not just "soft" but soft with intent
  marcato,      // marked вҖ” emphasis with bite
  morendo,      // dying away вҖ” not just diminuendo but *disappearing*
  sforzando,    // sudden force вҖ” the music startles itself
  espressivo,   // with expression вҖ” the performer decides
}
```

Finally, the **context** that grounds all these relationships into something playable:

```dart
/// Context is what turns relationships into absolutes
/// when (and only when) you need to render.
class MusicalContext {
  final Pitch referencePitch;    // now and only now do we pick "A4 = 440Hz"
  final Scale scale;
  final Tempo tempo;             // now proportions become durations
  final TimeSignature meter;     // now we know where downbeats fall
}

/// Rendering is a separate concern from composition.
/// You can reason about music entirely in the relational
/// domain and only "compile" to absolutes at the boundary.
List<MidiEvent> render(Music music, MusicalContext context) { ... }
List<LilypondToken> engrave(Music music, MusicalContext context) { ... }
```

---

**What I actually find interesting here** вҖ” and where my confidence is highest вҖ” is the decision to make intervals the primitive instead of pitches. This falls out of a group theory observation: the set of musical transformations (transpose, invert, retrograde) forms a group, and intervals are what's invariant under that group. You're modeling the *orbits*, not the *points*. Same instinct as physics choosing to model symmetries rather than coordinates.

Where my confidence thins: the `Tendency` type. I'm encoding Western common-practice tonal expectations, and that's a *specific theory of music*, not music itself. Modal jazz, Messiaen, gamelan вҖ” they have different gravity. The honest answer is that harmonic expectation might need to be a pluggable module rather than a core type. But I'd rather ship a vivid, slightly-wrong model that captures the *feeling* of dominant-to-tonic resolution than a hedged abstraction that captures nothing.

The other thing I'd argue over a beer: `Expression.espressivo` вҖ” "the performer decides" вҖ” is doing real philosophical work. It's an explicit acknowledgment that some musical concepts are *irreducibly human* and the best your data structure can do is point at the gap. Most music-as-code systems pretend the gap doesn't exist, and that's why they feel dead.

